      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">Yttrium is a silvery-white, soft metal. When heated, it burns with a red flame to produce yttrium oxide </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">– </text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">Y</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">2</text>
      </subsup>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">O</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">. In the reaction with water yttrium hydroxide – Y(OH</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">)</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238"> - is formed. On heating, yttrium also reacts with nitrogen, phosphorus and the halogens. It was named after the Swedish town of Ytterby. Yttrium was discovered by Johan Gadolin in 1794 and first obtained by Friedrich Wöhler in 1828.</text>
